Devonshire, England":"Honiton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Enland, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Donnett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English:  See  Dunnett  .","2  Scottish:  See  Dunnet  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dunnett","meanings":["Scottish: variant of <b>Dunnet</b>, a habitational name from Dunnet in Caithness.","English: from the Old French personal name <i>Donet</i>, <i>Donat</i>, from Latin <i>Donatus</i> (see   Donat  ). <i>Donatus</i> was the name of several Christian saints and was popular in France and Italy, whence it may have been brought to England.","English: habitational name from Downhead in Somerset or Donhead in Wiltshire, both named from Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill, down’ + Old English <i>hēafod</i> ‘head, end’."]},{"name":"Dunnet","meanings":["1  Scottish: locative name from Dunnet (Caithness).","2  English: see   Dunnett  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Donnett was born in 1326, her father, Henry Donnett, was 25 and her mother, Christian Oliver, was 23. She had at least 1 daughter with Richard Tremenent. She died in 1379, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1326–1379":"1326–1379","1312–1345":"1312–1345","1342–1374":"1342–1374","1301–1364":"1301–1364","1303–1369":"1303–1369","1326":"1326","1369":"1369","1303":"1303","1379":"1379","1345":"1345","1301":"1301","1312":"1312","1342":"1342","1364":"1364","1374":"1374","Of Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of Englan